<F P=100> AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   APLA Commander Reportedly Claims Shooting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1602151894 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1449 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1602151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg Feb 16 SAPA -- A caller claiming to be 
Azanian People's Liberation Army [APLA] Commander Karl Zimbiri 
on Wednesday afternoon claimed repsonsibility for an attack in 
south-east Johannesburg that left two Alberton traffic officers 
critically wounded and a woman injured. Police said earlier the 
three were shot by the occupants of a bakkie [pick-up truck] the 
officers stopped near Alberton on Wednesday morning. 
  Police spokesman Lt Deon Peens said in a statement Mr H R J 
Killian, 35, was wounded and the main artery in one of his legs 
was severed, while Mr H van der Westhuizen, 44, was shot in the 
head. They were admitted to hospital. A woman, whose name has 
not been released, was wounded in the buttocks while she was 
sitting in a taxi near the scene of the shooting. 
  Commander "Zimbiri" used a pre-arranged code in his call but 
there was no other way SAPA could independently verify the 
authenticity of the call. 
  He said the Alberton attack killed three officers -- 
"whites, 
naturally." There was no immediate explanation for the 
discrepency between his account of the attack and the police 
version. 
  The caller added the attack formed part of a "farewell 
programme" for APLA Commander Sabelo Phama who died in a motor 
accident in Tanzania last week. 
  "Zimbiri" claimed the death had been no accident and that 
Phama had been assassinated in a plot jointly planned by South 
Africa's National Intelligence Services and the USA's CIA. 
  APLA is the armed wing of the Pan Africanist Congress of 
Azania. 

</TEXT>

