<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> PHILIPPINES </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Official Sees No Links Between MNLF and Abu Sayaf </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1502022394 Manila MANILA BULLETIN in English 11 Feb 94 p 26 </F>
<F P=103> BK1502022394 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sel A. Baysa] </F>
  [Text] A top military official said yesterday he sees no 
direct links between the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) 
and the Abu Sayaf, a breakaway group of the MNLF. 
  "There is no sufficient proof to show of a tie-up between 
the 
Abu Sayaf and the MNLF. On the contrary, the Abu Sayaf is bent 
on sabotaging the ongoing peace talks between the MNLF and the 
government," Brigadier General Rene S. Dado, AFP [Armed Forces 
of the Philippines] Civil Relations Service (CRS) chief, said. 
  He urged the MNLF to stop giving refuge to Abu Sayaf members 
in their camps to express the MNLF disapproval of their acts of 
terrorism. 
  "By doing so, the Abu Sayaf will be completely isolated and 
this makes peace-loving and enlightened Muslims happier," Dado 
added. 
  The CRS chief traced the MNLF's generosity to Abu Sayaf 
members to old ties among leaders of the two groups. 
  Dado said the Abu Sayaf has only 120 full-time members, not 
1,000 as earlier reported. 
  He denied reports on the guns smuggled in by the Abu Sayaf 
"which could not be confirmed by military units in the area 
where the arms landing was supposed to have taken place." 
  He said the Abu Sayaf has adopted a guerrilla strategy. 

</TEXT>

