<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kathmandu Becomes New Base for Northeast Militants </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WR0090D Bombay THE TIMES OF INDIA in English 5 Jan 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> 94WR0090D </F>
<F P=104>  Bombay THE TIMES OF INDIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Syed Zubair Ahmed: "Kathmandu, New Base for N-E </F>
Militants"] 
  [Text] Guwahati, Jan 4 -- After Bangladesh, where the 
Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI) of Pakistan is reportedly 
training and arming the underground outfits of the north-east 
Kathmandu is fast becoming another centre for such activities 
for the groups of this region, claim Army sources. 
  The latest rebel group to establish contact with the ISI in 
the Nepalese capital is the United Liberation Front of Asom 
(ULFA), according to the sources. This was corroborated by some 
ULFA activists who were arrested by the state police for 
allegedly taking part in the attack on a police station in 
Nagaon district recently. An arrested militant, Gowswami, 
revealed his outfit had a base in Kathmandu which was used for 
regrouping after the surrender of more than half of its cadres 
in March 1992. 
  According to the Army officials posted in Nagaland and 
Manipur, the other outfits which already have bases in Kathmandu 
are the Socialist Council of Nagaland (NSCN), the Boro Security 
Force (BSF) of Assam and their umbrella organisation, the United 
Liberation Front of Seven Sisters, floated recently, allegedly 
with the help of the ISI. 
  The secessionist groups of the Kashmir Valley have been 
using 
the Pakistan embassy in Kathmandu as their base since the 
beginning of 1992. In fact, the ISI managed to push many top 
Kashmiri insurgents into India via Nepal. The sources say this 
is routinely done to prevent these "important" militants from 
being captured or killed by them while crossing over to the 
Valley from Pakistan. The modus operandi is simple. The rebels 
are trained in Pakistan and brought to Nepal on Pakistani 
passports. From Kathmandu they can enter India as Indians 
without arousing suspicion. 
  The Pakistan embassy in Kathmandu is being used as a base. 
This is, perhaps, not in the knowledge of the Nepalese 
government, unlike the Bangladesh government, sources claim. The 
Kathmandu base is a centre of indoctrination, where the ISI's 
job is to motivate the rebels of the north-east and provide 
logistical support. 
  The state police officials suspect that the recent spurt in 
violence by the ULFA was the result of its senior cadres 
regrouping in Kathmandu. They, however, rule out direct 
involvement of the ISI in the killing of four policemen in the 
attack on the Nagaon police station by the ULFA. 
  The defence sources also revealed the presence of an LTTE 
base in Moreh, a town located on the Indo-Myanmar border, where 
over 4,000 Tamilians from Myanmar settled several decades ago. 
But the threat from the Sri Lankan outfit is not great as its 
strength is negligible, say the sources. What they fear is a 
permanent liaison between the LTTE and the NSCN (I-M faction). 
"So far, we have no evidence to that effect," said a senior Army 
officer. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

