<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TOT-94-008-L </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:Terrorism 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   1 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> EGYPT </F>
<H3> <TI>   Islamic Group Attacks Bus Carrying Romanians </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ministry Clarifies Bus Attack </H4>
<F P=102> NC1402191694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1740 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1402191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 14 Feb (MENA)--An Interior Ministry official 
source has stated that an initial inspection of the area where 
shots were fired at a minibus belonging to the Asyut Cement 
Plant in Asyut shows that six bullets were fired at the vehicle 
from the front and right sides, and that all of them were 
directed at the lower half of the bus. This meant that the 
persons who opened fire at the vehicle did not intend to harm 
any of the passengers, especially as the passengers were walking 
toward the bus and were about 20 meters from it, and no one 
attempted to intercept them. 
  The source explained that some workers had been dismissed 
from the plant, and it is possible that they may have carried 
out some actions in order to inflict damage on the plant. 
  The security source said that the Western media have 
hastened 
in an unprecedented manner to exaggerate the incident and guess 
at the identity of the perpetrators. These media did not find 
in the minibus anything to satisfy their desire to distort the 
state of security and stability in Egypt, so they reported that 
it was a tourist bus. 
  The source called on the Western media to be accurate in 
reports that could harm the country's interests. The source 
affirmed that the Interior Ministry issues accurate statements 
about any incident. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-22966 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptot008__l94067" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TOT-94-008-L </AU>
