<H3> <TI>   Reiteration of Fatwa Against Salman Rushdie </TI></H3>
<H4>   No Plans To `Send Gunmen' Against Rushdie </H4>
<F P=102> NC1602103994 Paris AFP in English 0931 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1602103994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tehran, Feb 16 (AFP) -- [passage omitted] In an 
interview with the TEHRAN TIMES on Wednesday, Iran's speaker of 
parliament 'Ali Akbar Nateq-Nuri urged the West "not to stand by 
the wicked man who has hurt the feelings of over one billion 
Moslems," with his book. 
  "We advise Western countries not to spoil their relations 
with Iran because of the apostate Rushdie," he said. 
  Iran's present leaders have upheld the verdict and a 
religious foundation here has put a reward of more than $2 
million on Rushdie's head. 
  The speaker reaffirmed Khomeyni's "fatwa" (Islamic decree), 
saying Iran "would not retreat or make any changes in its 
position." 
  He accused Western countries of using Rushdie as a "weapon" 
to pressure the Islamic republic and urged Moslems to kill the 
author "whenever and wherever possible." However, he stressed 
Iran had no plans to send gunmen to kill Rushdie. [passage 
omitted] 

