<H3> <TI>   Sadiq al-Mahdi Blames Government for Mosque Attack </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1402203094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1915 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1402203094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Algiers, 14 Feb (MENA)--Al-Sadiq al-Mahdi, 
former Sudanese prime minister and opposition leader, has 
accused the Sudanese Government of responsibility for the [4 
February] armed attack against a mosque in Khartoum. He said 
the government has facilitated the entry of extremists from 
various countries of the world into Sudan. Addressing the Ansar 
al-Sunnah group, whose mosque was attacked last week, al-Mahdi 
said that the government has opened the country's doors to 
extremists who only believe in violence and reject any dialogue 
to resolve differences. 
  In statements published by the Algerian French-language 
paper 
EL WATAN today, al-Mahdi added that this incident, which left 16 
people dead, is regarded as the most serious in Sudan since the 
military coup carried out by 'Umar al-Bashir in 1989. 
  He noted that Sudan has become a place of refuge for all the 
extremists from the various countries of the world, including 
the Egyptian Islamic groups, the Tunisian Islamic Ennahda 
Movement, the Moroccan al-'Adl wa al-Ihsan Group, and the 
Algerian Islamic Salvation Front, as well as leader of the 
Sudanese Islamic Front Hasan al-Turabi. 
  The Algerian EL WATAN said that 50 leaders of these groups 
will form a council that will meet regularly in Sudan. There is 
already a smaller council consisting of 15 top leaders, 
including Algerian FIS leaders Abbassi Madani and Ali Belhadj. 
The paper noted that after their arrest, Rached Ghannouchi, 
leader of the Tunisian Islamic Ennahda Movement, has become the 
most important figure in this council. 
  The paper wondered whether the extremists admitted into the 
country by the Sudanese government were behind the armed attack 
that took place against the mosque of the Ansar al-Sunnah group, 
which is opposed to the government and is being persecuted by 
the Sudanese authorities. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

