<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Corsican Nationalists Announce End of Eight-Month Truce </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702083294 Paris AFP in English 0406 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1702083294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ajaccio, Corsica, Feb 17 (AFP) -- The banned 
Corsican National Liberation Front (FLNC) announced early 
Thursday that it was resuming its military activities after an 
eight-month truce. 
  At a clandestine press conference held at a remote spot in 
southern Corsica, an FLNC spokesman flanked by about 100 
heavily-armed and hooded militants, announced the end of the 
truce declared on June 22 last year. 
  Most of the FLNC leadership was present, seated at a table 
beneath a banner reading "FLNC: The people has risen up. It 
must go forward." 
  The Corsican nationalist movement said its decision to 
resume 
its military activities "reflects our determination not to be 
fobbed off with dud promises or satisfied with a few concessions 
involving institutional gadgets or a heap of cash." 
  The FLNC said a visit by Prime Minister Edouard Balladur on 
February 1 had "dissipated any ambiguity" about government 
policy. It said government policy in Corsica was "stamped with 
the seal of colonialism." 
  In view of the government's "intransigence" the FLNC said 
"we 
will resume our fight at all levels." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

