<H3> <TI>   ELN Said Threatening Candidates, Businessmen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0103043594 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0130 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0103043594 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jesus Garzon; from the "TV Today" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The National Liberation Army [ELN] guerrillas are 
reportedly financing political campaigns in Casanare, according 
to Colonel Alfonso Plazas Vega. The former commander of the 
Cavalry Academy, which in 1987 assumed control of the Justice 
Palace during the bloody takeover by the 19 April Movement, said 
the guerrillas are holding contacts with candidates through 
third parties to finance their campaigns. 
  [Begin recording] [Plazas] I am talking about candidates for 
governor and candidates for mayor in the municipalities of 
Yopal, Tauramena, and Aguazul. 
  [Government Minister Fabio Villegas] I do not believe the 
guerrillas have that kind of power in the political campaigns in 
Casanare. I am not aware that they are trying to exert 
influence on the political development of the region. 
  [Former President Julio Cesar Turbay Ayala] If that were the 
case, it must be condemned. [end recording] 
  According to Col. Plazas, the guerrillas are extorting 
businessmen by means of this system in Casanare. 
  [Begin Plazas recording] They are threatening candidates and 
asking them for allowances and if the allowances are not given 
they are included on a list of future kidnap victims in order to 
get the money anyway. [end recording] 
  Plazas Vega said that to solve the problem in Casanare, it 
is 
necessary to appoint military governors and mayors in that 
region of the country. 

</TEXT>

