<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TOT-94-010-L </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:Terrorism 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   10 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Update on, Reactions to Hebron Mosque Massacre </TI></H3>
<H4>   Settlers Comment at Goldstein Funeral </H4>
<F P=102> TA2702183094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1800 GMT 27 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2702183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Barukh Goldstein was buried in Qiryat Arba' 
this evening after a funeral procession from Jerusalem. The 
burial site at Qiryat Arba' is temporary, and his body will be 
moved eventually to the Jewish cemetery in Hebron. Speakers 
eulogizing Goldstein praised both the man and his actions. Mark 
Weiss was at the funeral: 
  Eulogies were recited at the Shamgar funeral parlor in 
Jerusalem and at the yeshiva in Qiryat Arba', and the message at 
both venues was militant and uncompromising. Speakers praised 
the massacre as a selfless act committed on behalf of the Jewish 
people as a whole. The victims were described not as innocent 
worshippers, but as the people who stabbed innocent Jews and the 
descendants of the Hebron residents who murdered almost the 
entire Jewish population of the town in 1929. A million Arabs 
are not worth the fingernail of one Jew, said one of the 
speakers. We are all Goldstein, shouted one of the mourners at 
one stage. Again and again, the speakers denounced the 
government and the media, and above all the fact that an armed 
Palestinian police force is about to be established. All this, 
together with the fact that Dr. Goldstein had repeatedly treated 
the victims of Arab terror, combined to create a situation where 
he just couldn't take it any more. All the eulogizers said 
Goldstein should be praised as a righteous man. A few hundred 
people attended the eulogies in Jerusalem. Many hundreds more 
joined in at Qiryat Arba'. [passage omitted] 
  For many other mourners, the most radical elements among the 
settlers, the funeral was an occasion to come together and 
express solidarity. And, that was definitely the feeling of a 
community under siege. There was intense hostility toward 
journalists, and much of the talk among the crowd was of a witch 
hunt and the possibility of informers planted within the 
settlements. 

</TEXT>

