<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Update on, Reactions to Hebron Mosque Massacre </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kakh Members Declare Defiance of Orders </H4>
<F P=102> TA0203201294 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0203201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Judy Lotz video report] </F>
  [Text] Restrictive orders were issued today also against 
residents of the settlement of Tapuah in Samaria. Judy Lotz met 
two of them, who declared they will disobey the orders: 
  [Begin recording] [Lotz] What does your order say, David? 
  [David Axelrod] My order says that I may not enter Hebron 
and Qiryat Arba' for three months, starting yesterday. 
  [Lotz] Did you have to turn in your gun? 
  [Axelrod] I did not receive this order, but I heard it 
exists. 
  [Lotz] Did they come to take away your gun? 
  [Axelrod] They left notice that I should turn it in. 
  [Lotz] Did you? 
  [Axelrod] I did not, and I have no such intention. 
  [Lotz] You are violating the law, are you not? 
  [Axelrod] Am I? Forsaking Jews to be murdered is a violation 
of our beliefs. 
  [Binyamin Ze'ev Kahana] I do not believe people will turn in 
their guns. I find this hard to believe. I believe people will 
rather sit in jail. 
  [Lotz] Will you turn in your gun? 
  [Kahana] I will turn in nothing. I find these orders 
insignificant. They are illegal, immoral, and unreasonable. 
  [Lotz] Will you travel to Hebron and Nabulus, in defiance of 
the orders? 
  [Kahana] I will go anywhere I please in this country. [end 
recording] 
  The police arrested today Eyal Noqed, another Kakh activist, 
who is one of the five the police are seeking to place under 
administrative detention. Our police affairs correspondent Uri 
Kohen-Aharonov has learned that Noqed was captured in an 
apartment in Ra'anana, following intelligence information. 
Currently, there are two Kakh members in police detention. 
Qiryat Arba' residents fear that exile orders will be issued 
this evening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

