<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> KUWAIT </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bomb Explodes at Cinema in Khaytan During Ramadan </TI></H3>
<H4>   Cinema Chief Blames Muslim Militants </H4>
<F P=102> NC0203222494 Paris AFP in English 2127 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0203222494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait City, March 2 (AFP) -- A bombing at a Kuwaiti 
cinema on Monday was carried out by Moslem militants, the owner 
of Kuwait's movie houses said in remarks published Wednesday. 
  "The blast was probably a religious warning due to the holy 
month of Ramadan," Yusuf al-Halabi, manager of the Kuwait 
National Cinema Company, told the ARAB TIMES. 
  "Last year we received a threat at the same time but it was 
not carried out," he added. 
  A security source who requested anonymity, however, said he 
believed Iraqi agents planted the bomb. 
  The Interior Ministry first said two people were slightly 
wounded in the blast, but a high-ranking police officer said 
only a guard suffered a slight head wound. 
  The Interior Ministry stepped up security measures around 
the 
nine cinemas in Kuwait City after Monday's bombing, sources said. 
  Attacks on cinemas, video shops, show business poeple and 
music stores, which are considered by fundamentalists as 
activities contrary to Islam, began after Kuwait was freed from 
a seven-month Iraqi occupation, in February 1991. 

</TEXT>

