<H3> <TI>   BKA Paper Reveals Steinmetz as RAF Member </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ministry, BKA Deny Report </H4>
<F P=102> AU0203105094 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
1 Mar 94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> AU0203105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE report: "Nothing Was Hushed Up in </F>
the Steinmetz Case"] 
  [Text] Frankfurt, 28 February -- The FRG Interior Ministry 
and the Federal Office of Criminal Investigation (BKA) denied on 
Monday that disagreeable findings on a leading role of informer 
Steinmetz in the Red Army Faction (RAF) had been held back. 
They also denied press reports that the author of a relevant 
report in the BKA had been transferred against his will by 
Interior Minister Kanther (Christian Democratic Union). The 
spokesman of the Interior Ministry reported that Kanther and 
Schelter, state secretary in the Interior Ministry, neither 
expressed the wish nor gave the instruction to transfer the 
official. According to the BKA statement, the authors of the 
report saying that the informer was probably a "leading member" 
of the RAF had themselves evaluated the paper as unfit to be 
used by a court. This means that it is unsuited for 
investigating files of the public prosecutor, but it is an 
assessment. However, the authors had never been urged by 
superiors or external authorities to change or withdraw the 
report. The contents of the report has been taken into account 
in the current investigations, also regarding Steinmetz, and 
were sent to the Federal Public Prosecutor's Office on 26 
October 1993. The internal transfer of the head of the section 
for terrorism was carried out in the BKA alone and with the 
agreement of the official, it was stated. Meanwhile, the BKA 
has tried to find out who might have passed on the controversial 
information to the press. Since the beginning of last week, the 
prosecuting authority is carrying out investigations in the BKA 
because of the suspicion that official secrets were disclosed. 

</TEXT>

