<H3> <TI>   Regional Guerrilla Report 7 March 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0803135994 </F>
<F P=103> PA0803135994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on regional guerrilla activities and clashes with 
government military units monitored through 7 March; source 
follows in parentheses after each item. 
<H5>  Colombia </H5>
  Seven Caqueta and Cauca government officials kidnapped by 
FARC (Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) guerrillas were 
released unharmed on 1 March after being held captive for nearly 
a week. Simultaneously, military forces arrested 10 alleged 
guerrillas in Bolivar. In another incident that has occurred in 
Bolivar, a UP (Patriotic Union) guerrilla was killed during a 
clash with a military patrol. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in 
Spanish 2 Mar 94 p 8a) 
  At least seven guerrillas have been killed and four arrested 
by Army units in several clashes that have occurred in Sucre, 
Santander, Boyaca, Norte de Boyaca, Cauca and Casanare; in 
another incident, the ELN (Army of National Liberation) has 
kidnapped Argelia Mayor Carlos Ivan Agrada. (Santa Fe de Bogota 
Inravision Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 1 Mar 94) 
  As the election draws nearer, extremist forces are 
continuing 
their attacks against candidates for public office. 
Unidentified individuals have killed Evaristo Amaya Morales, La 
Uribe mayoral candidate, while he was campaigning in Meta 
Department. In addition, a terrorist group detonated an 
explosive device while congressional candidate Telesforo Pedraza 
was campaigning in Huila Department. The government has 
announced it will not reschedule elections due to political 
violence. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 26 Feb 94 
pp. 1a, 6a) 
<H5>  Guatemala </H5>
  Official sources have reported a Guatemalan National 
Revolutionary Unity (URNG) column has attacked a military base 
in the northern Department of Quiche. A UN delegation was 
visiting the base at the moment of the attack. The Army Press 
and Information Department (Dide) has said a UN Human Rights 
delegation was at the base at the time and was able to witness 
the attack. Dide has also said the attack, which occurred on 2 
March, is clear evidence of the URNG's lack of willingness to 
negotiate peace. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1701 GMT 5 Mar 94) 
  Members of the National Police Department deactivated two 
explosive devices on 27 February. Both bombs carried subversive 
propaganda and were found in Guatemala City, one behind the 
municipal building, the other hidden inside a bench at the 
central park. (Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 2 Mar 94 
p. 18) 

</TEXT>

