Document Title:Terrorism 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   6 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Legal Moves on Kakh, Kahana Hay Viewed With `Concern' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0603115194 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 6 Mar 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> TA0603115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Washington by Hayim Shibi] </F>
  [Excerpts] The Clinton administration is close to deciding 
to place the Kakh and Kahana Hay movements on the list of terror 
organizations. [passage omitted] 
  If indeed the U.S. Justice Department decides to Place Kakh 
and Kahana Hay on the list of terror organizations -- the very 
membership in which constitutes a criminal act -- this would be 
the first time in U.S. history that Jewish organizations will be 
on that list, along with Arab terror organizations. 
  This might create a situation in which IDF [Israel Defense 
Forces] reserve officers who, according to Kahana Hay leaders, 
conduct training camps for the organization members in the 
United States, might be listed as members of a terror 
organization and become a target of a criminal investigation by 
the FBI. 
  Mike Gozovsky, the Kahana Hay Movement spokesman, told our 
correspondent that the organization includes 8,000 members who 
pay annual membership fees of $36 each. A fund-raising dinner 
the movement organized in New York recently, was attended by 
some 500 people who paid $125 each. 
  Another serious problem that might arise if the 
organizations 
are listed with other terror organizations, would be that 
raising funds for them would be banned. Israeli sources in 
Washington view with concern the administration acceptance of 
the Palestinian request to hold up "fund-raising campaigns for 
extremists" in Israel. It is feared that a broad legal 
definition would create a dangerous precedent which will create 
difficulties for a wide range of fund- raising campaigns in the 
future. 
  It should be noted that the Judaea, Samaria, and Gaza 
Settlements Council, the City of Ari'el, and a series of Israeli 
public institutions have a regular fund-raising organ based in 
the United States. Americans also make donations to the belt 
neighborhoods around Jerusalem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

