<H3> <TI>   Security Makes Arrests for February Bombings </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Foreign Parties' Financing `Afghans' </H4>
<F P=102> PM0803084094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 5 Mar 94 p4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0803084094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Jordan Accuses `Foreign Parties' of </F>
Financing `Afghans' and Planning Explosions"] 
  [Text] Amman, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- A senior Jordanian 
security source has accused foreign parties of perpetrating the 
explosions that have recently occurred and continue to occur in 
Jordan, but he emphasized that these parties are neither states 
nor governments. 
  The source's statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT came after the 
discovery of five bombs in an area west of the capital Amman. 
The source said that foreign parties, now known to the security 
authorities, are behind the explosions and are linked to 
incidents which have occurred in more than one Arab country, and 
are currently providing aid for the so-called "Afghan Arabs." 
He added that the "Afghan" leader now detained and under 
interrogation with his group in Jordan is 45 years old and a 
resident of al-Baq'ah refugee camp north of Amman, and that most 
members of that organization come from that camp. 
  On the five hand grenades found by the security authorities, 
he said that they were of the U.S. M-26 type and were hidden in 
a plastic bag when they were discovered near the industrial area 
adjacent to the Civil Defense Department in the area of Bayadir 
Wadi al-Sayr west of Amman. 
  The source did not rule out the possibility that they were 
planted by "Jordanian Afghans" particularly as they were similar 
to the devices used in previous explosions. He said that a 
security commission has been formed to investigate and find out 
the source of these bombs and why they were planted in that area 
close to the Civil Defense Department building. 
  A citizen had told the security authorities that as he was 
walking around in his workshop close to the Civil Defense 
Department, he discovered the bombs in a plastic bag, and called 
in the explosives experts to defuse them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

