<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   St. Petersburg Official Sees Large Increase in Kidnapping </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0703164694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1619 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0703164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The St.Petersburg interior board predicts a sharp 
increase in the number of hostage seizures and terrorist acts, 
the head of the regional board for combat against organized 
crime Sergey Sidorenko told INTERFAX. 
  Last year the interior board servicemen liberated 47 
hostages, including 6 children. During the past two months 12 
hostages have been liberated. In the meantime, Sidorenko 
believes that criminals actually seize at least twice as many 
people. 
  In his opinion, an increase in hostages in the near future 
will be caused by the aggravating competition among criminal 
gangs for the spheres of influence in St. Petersburg. In this 
connection, Sidorenko noted a considerable rise in illegal arms 
supplies. According to him, since the beginning of this year, 
the regional board for combat against organized crime has 
confiscated about 70 firearms, supplied mainly from Estonia. 
Sidorenko pointed out that it is difficult to trace arms 
supplies due to the lack of cooperation with the police of the 
Baltic states. "Sometimes it is easier for us to cooperate with 
FBI and Scotland Yard than with the Baltic states' police," he 
noted. 

</TEXT>

