<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Prosecutor Denies Dissolution of RAF </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703175794 </F>
<F P=103> AU0703175794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Wiesbaden/Karlsruhe (DPA) -- The Office of the 
Federal Public Prosecutor has rejected the view of members of 
the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution [BfV] 
that the terrorist Red Army Faction (RAF) has ceased to exist in 
its former form and as a single entity. The RAF has not given 
up its armed struggle, Rolf Hannich, deputy spokesman for the 
Office of the Federal Public Prosecutor said on Monday in an 
interview with DPA. At the same time, he warned against assuming 
that the RAF no longer constitutes a terrorist threat. 
  It is true that in late October 1993, the majority of RAF 
prisoners, the so-called hard-liners around Brigitte Mohnhaupt, 
left the RAF. Nevertheless, one cannot assume that the RAF has 
given up its fight against the state. On the contrary, in its 
last command declaration of 2 November 1993, the RAF made it 
clear that it continues to be active as a terrorist group. One 
must assume that, despite the arrest in Bad Kleinen, the RAF 
remains capable of taking action, Hannich said. Hence, attacks 
have to be expected from the RAF command level in the future, 
too. 
  Hannich thus rejected an assessment by the Bavarian Office 
for the Protection of the Constitution that the RAF had ceased 
to exist as a single entity. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

