<H3> <TI>   `Red Zora' Expected To Carry Out New Terrorist Attacks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803144694 Munich FOCUS in German 7 Mar 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> AU0803144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich FOCUS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Mili's Explosive Dance on the Ice"] </F>
  [Text] According to findings by the Federal Office of 
Criminal Investigations (BKA) in Wiesbaden, the feminist 
extremist group "Red Zora," which was responsible for several 
bomb and arson attacks in 1987, is planning new acts of violence. 
  An internal BKA report quotes a strategy paper by "Red 
Zora." 
It announces "illegal militant organizing" to "destroy 
patriarchal power." 
  In a 38-page underground brochure entitled "Mili's Dance on 
the Ice," "Red Zora," which went underground in August 1988, is 
now again calling for attacks and punishment actions against 
persons and institutions that it holds responsible for the 
oppression of women, as the BKA analysis says. 
  In 1978, "Red Zora" attracted attention for the first time 
with attacks on sex shops. In 1984, there followed attacks on 
genetic laboratories and the Federal Constitutional Court. 
  In 1987, "Red Zora," which, according to the chief federal 
prosecutor's office, is an underground organization of the "Red 
Cells," set fire to the mother company of the Adler clothing 
company in Haibach near Aschaffenburg and another seven 
subsidiaries of the company. 
  At that time, the textile corporation was accused by "Red 
Zora" of exploiting women in South Korea. 

</TEXT>

