<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   11 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Failed Mortar Attacks on Heathrow Airport </TI></H3>
<H4>   Police Reopen Southern Runway </H4>
<F P=102> LD1103084094 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 0820 GMT 11 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1103084094 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The southern runway reopened at 7.30 am, the 
airport said. Terminal Four and roads around the airport were 
reopened during the night. 
  Some early morning flights were cancelled and others 
diverted 
before the terminal was opened. People inquiring about British 
Airways arrivals were advised to ring 081 759 2525. 
  A statement from the airport said: "Due to the closure of 
one 
runway, delays are likely on other inbound and outbound flights." 
  "Passengers can be assured that this morning's incident is 
being contained within Terminal Four and that their safety 
remains a top priority." 
  It said the airport usually used only one runway during the 
night. The southern runway was being used from 10.30pm last 
night. 
  The last plane to take off was at 11.25pm -- 35 minutes 
before the incident. 
  The last plane to land was a mail flight which touched down 
on the northern runway at 00.34am. 
  The latest incident follows a warning by Sinn Fein president 
Gerry Adams yesterday that there could be another attack like 
Wednesday's IRA strike on the airport, when four mortar bombs 
were fired from a vehicles in a car park at the Excelsior Hotel, 
on the Heathrow's northern border. 

</TEXT>

